So effectively swc replaces the descriptor that is used as the initializer on the class, but it is arguable that it really should do that, because it is also defining it on the prototype.  Because tsc "properly" emits it as a class field, it has the right behaviour from what people expect for a class field and is defined in the specification, but it masks the decorator on the prototype.

Because decorators are experimental and broken proposal, the behaviour is undefined.  We should not/cannot disable `useDefineForClassFields` as the runtime behaviour of class fields becomes non-spec compliant.  It feels like the experimental and broken specification is incompatible with the current ECMAScript specification.  Using experimental decorators is a bad idea.

Also, without the decorator at all, the behaviour between swc and tsc differ as well in a slightly important way:

Given:

```ts
export class A {
  foo?: number;
}
console.log(new A().foo);
```

You get the following from `tsc`:

```js
export class A {
    foo;
}
console.log(new A().foo);
```

And the following from `swc`:

```js
export class A {
}
console.log(new A().foo);
```

